<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-542-001  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 542 001.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  March 1990 v3 n3 p233(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Burns andamp; Venit on desktop publishing. (Pro Tips) (tutorial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burns, Diane; Venit, S.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Desktop publishingTutorialDocument Preparation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Burns andamp; Venit on Desktop PublishingandM;Traditionally, designers and typesetters have used a typecasting referencebook, in which blocks of greek or dummy text appear in many differenttypefaces and sizes, to estimate how long manuscripts will be when they're intype.andM;With laser printers, word processors, and page layout applications that letyou typeset text yourself, it's easy to estimate document lengths without areference book.andP;  Here's how:andM;1.andP;  With the word processor or page layout package you'll use for the finalpage production, set the margins or columns as you would for the finaldesign.andM;2.andP;  Type one paragraph of dummy text 200 characters long (or the averageparagraph length for the manuscript--usually shorter for narrow-columnformats such as newsletters).andP;  Format the paragraph in the font selected forthe final design.andM;3.andP;  Duplicate the paragraph as many times as necessary to fill one page.andM;4.andP;  Count the number of paragraphs required to fill the page, and multiplythat number by 200--or your dummy paragraph length--to estimate the charactercount per page.andM;5.andP;  To estimate the number of pages a manuscript will produce, divide theresult of step 4 into the total character count.andM;6.andP;  If you need to give an author an estimate of how long a manuscript shouldbe, multiply the result of step 4 by the total number of pages allowed forthe final document.andP;  This will give you the total number of characters; toconvert to a word count, divide the character count by six.andM;Diane Burns and S. Venit have written nine books, and their company, TechArt,in San Francisco, has produced camera-ready pages for more than 40 books.andO;</TEXT></DOC>